items.title: Golf carts causing serious injuries to children
items.summary: As golf carts become increasingly popular in communities beyond the fairway, new research shows, a significant number of children are being seriously injured while using them.

alternate.title: Golf carts causing serious injuries to children

items.title: Riding a slide while on a parent's lap increases the risk of injury
items.summary: Going down a slide on a parent's lap can lead to a broken leg for small children. An estimated 352,698 children less than 6 years of age were injured on slides in the United States from 2002 through 2015, and many of those injuries were leg fractures.

alternate.title: Riding a slide while on a parent's lap increases the risk of injury

items.title: Carbohydrates may be the key to a better malaria vaccine
items.summary: An international research team has shown for the first time that carbohydrates on the surface of malaria parasites play a critical role in malaria's ability to infect mosquito and human hosts. The discovery also suggests steps that may improve the only malaria vaccine approved to protect people against Plasmodium falciparum malaria -- the most deadly form of the disease.

alternate.title: Carbohydrates may be the key to a better malaria vaccine

thumbnail.title: Carbohydrates may be the key to a better malaria vaccine

items.title: New Orleans greenery post-Katrina reflects social demographics more than hurricane impact
items.summary: Popular portrayals of "nature reclaiming civilization" in flood-damaged New Orleans, Louisianna, neighborhoods romanticize an urban ecology shaped by policy-driven socioecological disparities in redevelopment investment, ecologists argue.

alternate.title: New Orleans greenery post-Katrina reflects social demographics more than hurricane impact

items.title: Electric eels leap to deliver painful, Taser-like jolt
items.summary: The electric eel has always been noted for its impressive ability to shock and subdue its prey. It's recently become clear that electric eels also use a clever trick to deliver an intense, Taser-like jolt to potential predators: they leap from the water to target threatening animals, humans included, above water. Now, a researcher has measured (and experienced) just how strong that jolt can be.

alternate.title: Electric eels leap to deliver painful, Taser-like jolt

thumbnail.title: Electric eels leap to deliver painful, Taser-like jolt
